Wait, really dumb question, how do Horeshoe crab eyes work? What exactly are they able to see?
Isnt that giant shell really obscuring?
well
they have 9 eyes
and a bunch of photo receptors on their tail
WOW
one MRE, two ME, two VE, two LE and two LRE
for the left diagram
their lateral eyes (LE) are the big ones. those see color and decently well in a pretty wide angle view

the Median Eyes are also somewhat complex and are on either side of the horn on their front. they look up and only see UV light. those tell if the moon is full or not because thats how they plan their breeding
the Median Rudimentary points forward and Lateral Rudimentary eyes point up, but all only see shades. mostly used (hypothesized) to see shadows of things that pass over them
the ventral eyes are underneath and help them navigate and see what theyre eating
and the tail and back are filled with photoreceptors that also just tell shadows

Whoah. I had no idea they were so sophisticated. 

Thats really cool!
thats not even the coolest part
their lateral eyes are like that of a fly. made of thousands of tiny eyes.
each one has a rhabdom, which is a crystal structure, that is filled with opsins, the proteins that say "HEY YOURE SEEING LIGHT"
during the day, its straight and thin
but once the sun sets and hits a certain angle, they change
the structures fold in on themselves and they increase the number of opsins 10x
their lens opens up, and they let in as much light as possible, and that structure with the increased opsins is absorbing as many photons as possible.
because of that, they can see just as well at night as they can during the day
and then in the morning at the first glimpse of daylight (true uv daylight), they shed the entire internal eye structure and regrow it from scratch in 30 minutes
and that was my thesis
